  'mechanism mechanism surface silanization interface chemistry hydrolyzed silanes condense with hydroxylated surfaces or with each other creating functional organic-inorganic interfaces. surface hydroxyl density humidity and silane concentration control apparent coverage. surface orientation and multilayer formation matter more than molecular stereochemistry. interface chemistry surface silane interface silica modification glass functionalization composite adhesion biosensor immobilization summary hydrolyzed silanes condense with hydroxylated surfaces or with each other creating functional organic-inorganic interfaces. steps silane hydrolysis surface condensation curing and removal of physisorbed silane best for silica modification glass functionalization composite adhesion biosensor immobilization rate law and stereochemistry surface hydroxyl density humidity and silane concentration control apparent coverage. surface orientation and multilayer formation matter more than molecular stereochemistry.'
