  'Mechanistic organic chemistry',
  '',
  '',
  0,
  '',
  '["EAS","aromaticity","electrophile","directing effects"]',
  'record.html?type=dossier&id=aromatic-eas',
  'dossiers.html?id=aromatic-eas',
  'data:image/svg+xml;charset=UTF-8,%3Csvg%20xmlns%3D%22http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg%22%20width%3D%22640%22%20height%3D%22420%22%20viewBox%3D%220%200%20640%20420%22%3E%3Crect%20width%3D%22640%22%20height%3D%22420%22%20fill%3D%22%23f5f5f7%22%2F%3E%3Cpath%20d%3D%22M84%20278%20190%2096l106%20182H84Zm260-152h170v170H344V126Zm-174%2044h276%22%20fill%3D%22none%22%20stroke%3D%22%231d1d1f%22%20stroke-width%3D%2212%22%20stroke-linecap%3D%22round%22%20stroke-linejoin%3D%22round%22%20opacity%3D%22.34%22%2F%3E%3Ccircle%20cx%3D%22190%22%20cy%3D%2296%22%20r%3D%2220%22%20fill%3D%22%230071e3%22%2F%3E%3Ccircle%20cx%3D%22296%22%20cy%3D%22278%22%20r%3D%2220%22%20fill%3D%22%230071e3%22%2F%3E%3Ccircle%20cx%3D%22514%22%20cy%3D%22126%22%20r%3D%2218%22%20fill%3D%22%230071e3%22%2F%3E%3Ctext%20x%3D%2242%22%20y%3D%2258%22%20fill%3D%22%231d1d1f%22%20font-family%3D%22-apple-system%2CBlinkMacSystemFont%2CSegoe%20UI%2CArial%2Csans-serif%22%20font-size%3D%2224%22%20font-weight%3D%22700%22%3EDossier%3C%2Ftext%3E%3Ctext%20x%3D%2242%22%20y%3D%22355%22%20fill%3D%22%231d1d1f%22%20font-family%3D%22-apple-system%2CBlinkMacSystemFont%2CSegoe%20UI%2CArial%2Csans-serif%22%20font-size%3D%2236%22%20font-weight%3D%22800%22%3EAromatic%20Substitution%20Dossie%3C%2Ftext%3E%3Ctext%20x%3D%2242%22%20y%3D%22388%22%20fill%3D%22%236e6e73%22%20font-family%3D%22-apple-system%2CBlinkMacSystemFont%2CSegoe%20UI%2CArial%2Csans-serif%22%20font-size%3D%2220%22%20font-weight%3D%22600%22%3EMechanistic%20organic%20chemistry%20%C2%B7%20active%3C%2Ftext%3E%3C%2Fsvg%3E',
  '{"id":"aromatic-eas","title":"Aromatic Substitution Dossier","field":"Mechanistic organic chemistry","status":"active","maturity":81,"abstract":"A mechanism-first dossier for electrophilic aromatic substitution, connecting electrophile generation, sigma-complex stability, directing effects and loss of aromaticity.","keywords":["EAS","aromaticity","electrophile","directing effects"],"methods":["Mechanistic sequence mapping","Substituent-effect table","Counterexample register"],"observables":["Catalyst or acid activation","Ring activation or deactivation","Product regiochemistry"],"claims":["Benzene bromination requires electrophile activation in standard teaching examples.","Restoration of aromaticity explains substitution rather than permanent addition.","Substituent effects must be separated from reagent strength."],"limitations":["No kinetic dataset is included for comparing substituted rings.","Reactive electrophile identity can vary with conditions.","The dossier is a reasoning tool rather than a full computational study."],"reproducibility":[{"item":"Mechanistic steps stated","state":"complete"},{"item":"Terminology anchored","state":"complete"},{"item":"Rate data supplied","state":"missing"},{"item":"Regiochemical examples","state":"partial"}],"linked":[{"label":"Open Research Desk case","href":"research.html?case=aromatic-bromination"},{"label":"Open EAS atlas node","href":"atlas.html?id=eas"},{"label":"Open bromination record","href":"reagents.html?id=br2-febr3"}]}',
  'dossier dossier aromatic substitution dossier mechanistic organic chemistry active a mechanism-first dossier for electrophilic aromatic substitution connecting electrophile generation sigma-complex stability directing effects and loss of aromaticity. benzene bromination requires electrophile activation in standard teaching examples. restoration of aromaticity explains substitution rather than permanent addition. substituent effects must be separated from reagent strength. mechanistic organic chemistry eas aromaticity electrophile directing effects summary a mechanism-first dossier for electrophilic aromatic substitution connecting electrophile generation sigma-complex stability directing effects and loss of aromaticity. highlights claims benzene bromination requires electrophile activation in standard teaching examples. restoration of aromaticity explains substitution rather than permanent addition. substituent effects must be separated from reagent strength. references'
);
